00:51:13.150 --> 00:51:15.549
What was the process like
making the animated video

00:51:15.549 --> 00:51:16.340
in the first place?

00:51:16.340 --> 00:51:17.960
Do you have a lot
of input into that?

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:21.270
BENJAMIN SCHEUER:
Well, Peter is a-- he

00:51:21.270 --> 00:51:23.130
went to Cambridge in England.

00:51:23.130 --> 00:51:28.200
And he studied architecture
and oil painting

00:51:28.200 --> 00:51:31.020
because he likes making
three-dimensional things

00:51:31.020 --> 00:51:32.895
in two dimensions.

00:51:32.895 --> 00:51:34.436
And eventually, he
realized, you know

00:51:34.436 --> 00:51:37.920
what, I think actually I'm
supposed to be an animator.

00:51:37.920 --> 00:51:41.220
I want to tell stories, big
three-dimensional stories

00:51:41.220 --> 00:51:43.060
in two dimensions.

00:51:43.060 --> 00:51:47.560
And so we had a mutual
friend who connected us.

00:51:47.560 --> 00:51:51.150
And I'd finished
recording that song,

00:51:51.150 --> 00:51:53.050
"The Lion" on the
record "The Bridge"

00:51:53.050 --> 00:51:55.900
with Escapist Papers, my band.

00:51:55.900 --> 00:51:59.009
And so I called my
friend Alex and I said,

00:51:59.009 --> 00:52:00.425
I'm looking to
animate this video.

00:52:00.425 --> 00:52:01.780
And there's so many words in it.

00:52:01.780 --> 00:52:04.207
And I really want to
do it pretty literally.

00:52:04.207 --> 00:52:05.290
Do you know any animators?

00:52:05.290 --> 00:52:06.130
And he said, yeah,
you should talk

00:52:06.130 --> 00:52:07.300
to my friend Peter Baynton.

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:08.631
And so I went to meet Pete.

00:52:08.631 --> 00:52:10.130
I'd sent him the
song ahead of time.

00:52:10.130 --> 00:52:12.255
And he turned up at our
meeting with this cardboard

00:52:12.255 --> 00:52:16.160
guy he'd made with an Exacto
knife and a piece of cardboard.

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:20.641
And he said, what about
him as the main character?

00:52:20.641 --> 00:52:21.890
ALAN SEALES: It looks just me.

00:52:21.890 --> 00:52:22.848
BENJAMIN SCHEUER: Yeah.

00:52:22.848 --> 00:52:27.070
And I just kind of burst
into tears, I was so moved.

00:52:27.070 --> 00:52:29.232
And Pete and I talked.

00:52:29.232 --> 00:52:31.190
It took us about nine
months to make the video.

00:52:31.190 --> 00:52:36.910
And actually I met his mom at
the British Animation Awards,

00:52:36.910 --> 00:52:39.350
where Pete took home
the award for "The Lion"

00:52:39.350 --> 00:52:42.310
for public choice
for best music video.

00:52:42.310 --> 00:52:47.200
And Pete's mom said, I thought
that-- Peter was at home.

00:52:47.200 --> 00:52:49.165
And the kitchen floor
was covered in cardboard.

00:52:49.165 --> 00:52:51.470
And I didn't know
what was going on.

00:52:51.470 --> 00:52:55.330
And Pete, I really just
let him do his thing.

00:52:55.330 --> 00:52:57.415
He sent me an
animatic initially.

00:52:57.415 --> 00:52:59.040
And what an animatic
is, it's basically

00:52:59.040 --> 00:53:02.960
a slide show to the song,
which is kind of drawings

00:53:02.960 --> 00:53:05.750
of how the story would work.

00:53:05.750 --> 00:53:08.620
And one thing that was
really important to Peter

00:53:08.620 --> 00:53:10.310
was character.

00:53:10.310 --> 00:53:12.079
In the very beginning
of the video,

00:53:12.079 --> 00:53:13.620
there's a table with
all the pictures

00:53:13.620 --> 00:53:15.810
of all the lions in the family.

00:53:15.810 --> 00:53:18.770
And what's
fascinating about that

00:53:18.770 --> 00:53:22.150
is Peter followed every
single one of those characters

00:53:22.150 --> 00:53:23.400
on a journey through the song.

00:53:23.400 --> 00:53:24.996
There's no character
that doesn't

00:53:24.996 --> 00:53:26.120
have a journey in the song.

00:53:26.120 --> 00:53:29.530
And so it was very much about
telling everybody's story very

00:53:29.530 --> 00:53:31.920
specifically and being
really true to that.

00:53:31.920 --> 00:53:34.520
And there's no wasted time.

00:53:34.520 --> 00:53:37.080
Similar to the way Riya,
the photographer, works.

00:53:37.080 --> 00:53:38.650
Peter works the same way.

00:53:38.650 --> 00:53:42.105
And I love, man, I
loved working with him.

00:53:42.105 --> 00:53:43.730
And I don't have to
do a lot with Pete.

00:53:43.730 --> 00:53:45.770
I send him a song, and
I send him my ideas,

00:53:45.770 --> 00:53:47.290
and I let him get on with it.

00:53:47.290 --> 00:53:50.770
And he'll come back and say,
this is what we're doing.

00:53:50.770 --> 00:53:51.710
And it's awesome.

00:53:51.710 --> 00:53:54.770
And I hope to-- we're going
to make two more videos.

00:53:54.770 --> 00:53:57.465
And one day, I want to make an
animated feature film with him.

00:53:57.465 --> 00:53:59.840
We've made these little movies
for a little bit of money.

00:53:59.840 --> 00:54:03.630
One day, I want to go bother
Pixar and go get $10 million

00:54:03.630 --> 00:54:05.422
and make a real movie.

00:54:05.422 --> 00:54:07.380
I mean he's going to be
an extraordinary person

00:54:07.380 --> 00:54:08.500
to do that with.

00:54:08.500 --> 00:54:10.160
Radish Pictures is his company.

00:54:10.160 --> 00:54:13.530
Mark my words, in 10
years, Radish Pictures,

00:54:13.530 --> 00:54:16.697
they'll be fighting you
guys for real estate.

00:54:16.697 --> 00:54:18.030
ALAN SEALES: Oh, yeah, question?

00:54:18.030 --> 00:54:18.850
AUDIENCE: Hey, Ben.

00:54:18.850 --> 00:54:19.260
BENJAMIN SCHEUER: Hey.

00:54:19.260 --> 00:54:19.820
AUDIENCE: Kevin.

00:54:19.820 --> 00:54:21.819
I've been a fan of yours
since you played guitar

00:54:21.819 --> 00:54:24.170
in the production of "Tommy"
that I produced at Harvard.

00:54:24.170 --> 00:54:25.378
BENJAMIN SCHEUER: No kidding.

00:54:25.378 --> 00:54:27.050
Hey, man.

00:54:27.050 --> 00:54:28.920
AUDIENCE: Best
undergraduate production

00:54:28.920 --> 00:54:30.170
of "Tommy" guitar player ever.

00:54:30.170 --> 00:54:31.586
BENJAMIN SCHEUER:
Well, thank you.

00:54:31.586 --> 00:54:32.480
That was really fun.

00:54:32.480 --> 00:54:32.840
AUDIENCE: It was awesome.

00:54:32.840 --> 00:54:33.520
It was great.

00:54:33.520 --> 00:54:34.020
Yeah.

00:54:34.020 --> 00:54:34.520
Yeah.

00:54:34.520 --> 00:54:36.610
It was like 14 years ago.

00:54:36.610 --> 00:54:38.750
So like obviously, you're
a great songwriter.

00:54:38.750 --> 00:54:41.810
And 50 years ago, you might
be on like a Stephen Sondheim

00:54:41.810 --> 00:54:43.660
path, where you
just write musicals

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:45.810
and they start in Boston.

00:54:45.810 --> 00:54:48.102
And then they go to Broadway.

00:54:48.102 --> 00:54:49.560
Other than "Hamilton,"
I don't know

00:54:49.560 --> 00:54:52.610
if there are many like original
musicals coming to Broadway.

00:54:52.610 --> 00:54:57.090
So what does the career look
like for someone who wants

00:54:57.090 --> 00:54:58.470
to be a Broadway songwriter?

00:54:58.470 --> 00:55:01.860
And given like most of the
Broadway theaters right

00:55:01.860 --> 00:55:06.620
now are Disney or
movie adaptations,

00:55:06.620 --> 00:55:08.434
what are the plans
for your career?

00:55:08.434 --> 00:55:10.100
BENJAMIN SCHEUER:
Well, I wholeheartedly

00:55:10.100 --> 00:55:12.016
believe that making
records and making theater

00:55:12.016 --> 00:55:14.050
are not in opposition
to one another.

00:55:14.050 --> 00:55:16.790
They're, in fact,
the same thing.

00:55:16.790 --> 00:55:19.310
And that if you want to
write a show that you want

00:55:19.310 --> 00:55:22.980
to be successful, there's
so many tools that

00:55:22.980 --> 00:55:25.500
can reach beyond the
theater to get audiences

00:55:25.500 --> 00:55:26.795
that don't go to the theater.

00:55:26.795 --> 00:55:28.670
I mean the people who come
to see "The Lion," yeah,

00:55:28.670 --> 00:55:29.300
it's a theater audience.

00:55:29.300 --> 00:55:30.800
But it's also kids
who just hang out

00:55:30.800 --> 00:55:35.430
at Rockwood Music Hall,
kids who dig pop music

00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:36.390
or who dig folk music.

00:55:36.390 --> 00:55:41.590
And so I think that if
you're writing a show,

00:55:41.590 --> 00:55:42.900
release your singles.

00:55:42.900 --> 00:55:45.345
And if they don't work
as singles, rewrite them.

00:55:45.345 --> 00:55:46.720
And if then they
don't work, then

00:55:46.720 --> 00:55:48.380
probably your show
isn't going to work

00:55:48.380 --> 00:55:50.530
in the contemporary era.

00:55:50.530 --> 00:55:53.460
And if your songs are
compelling enough,

00:55:53.460 --> 00:55:55.501
then people don't even
know they're from a show.

00:55:55.501 --> 00:55:56.250
It doesn't matter.

00:55:56.250 --> 00:55:58.740
People don't need to see the
"Cookie-tin Banjo" video.

00:55:58.740 --> 00:56:00.850
If they like it, they don't need
to know it's from "The Lion."

00:56:00.850 --> 00:56:02.170
I mean it's a humble video.

00:56:02.170 --> 00:56:06.000
It's only been seen 125,000
times, which is nothing

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:08.602
in sort of big YouTube terms.

00:56:08.602 --> 00:56:10.810
But it's way more than people
who have seen the show.

00:56:10.810 --> 00:56:12.730
There's only 200
seats in the theater.

00:56:12.730 --> 00:56:19.180
So I would advise any songwriter
who's writing for the stage--

00:56:19.180 --> 00:56:22.357
and I do, in my group
of writer friends.

00:56:22.357 --> 00:56:24.440
And it's really a huge
community here in New York.

00:56:24.440 --> 00:56:26.616
I mean Sam Willmott is
an amazing songwriter.

00:56:26.616 --> 00:56:27.990
Jean Rose, an
amazing songwriter.

00:56:27.990 --> 00:56:29.910
Shaina Taub is an
amazing songwriter.

00:56:29.910 --> 00:56:34.710
These people are really
putting on creative, different

00:56:34.710 --> 00:56:37.960
sounding, excellent theater.

00:56:37.960 --> 00:56:39.872
I advise them to write
about themselves.

00:56:39.872 --> 00:56:41.830
Because man, if you can't
write about yourself,

00:56:41.830 --> 00:56:43.910
like good luck writing
about somebody else.

00:56:43.910 --> 00:56:45.534
Good luck telling
somebody else's truth

00:56:45.534 --> 00:56:48.060
if you have a hard
time telling your own.

00:56:48.060 --> 00:56:50.567
Beyond that, yeah, I think
thinking of different ways

00:56:50.567 --> 00:56:51.150
to do theater.

00:56:51.150 --> 00:56:54.540
I mean different venues.

00:56:54.540 --> 00:56:55.874
Anything goes.

00:56:55.874 --> 00:56:58.290
I mean I was told that doing
a one-person autobiographical

00:56:58.290 --> 00:56:59.600
musical was a terrible idea.

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:01.667
And I was like, OK, cool.

00:57:01.667 --> 00:57:02.750
Maybe no one will like it.

00:57:02.750 --> 00:57:03.920
But that's what I
feel like doing.

00:57:03.920 --> 00:57:05.780
And I don't think
there really are rules.

00:57:05.780 --> 00:57:07.850
And I think the young
producers, some of whom

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:11.530
are in this room
today, they dig that.

00:57:11.530 --> 00:57:13.265
And they'll help
you make your thing.

00:57:13.265 --> 00:57:15.390
If you believe wholeheartedly,
and you put together

00:57:15.390 --> 00:57:17.390
a good team of people,
and you have a cool story

00:57:17.390 --> 00:57:20.310
to tell in a cool way,
like it'll totally work.

00:57:20.310 --> 00:57:21.600
That's what I think.

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:23.100
AUDIENCE: And I
work on YouTube now.

00:57:23.100 --> 00:57:25.273
So I'll see what I can do about
getting that play count up.

00:57:25.273 --> 00:57:26.439
BENJAMIN SCHEUER: Great man.

00:57:26.439 --> 00:57:28.249
Thank you very much.

00:57:28.249 --> 00:57:28.790
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:57:28.790 --> 00:57:29.820
BENJAMIN SCHEUER: Hey.

00:57:29.820 --> 00:57:31.352
AUDIENCE: You talked
about-- I mean

00:57:31.352 --> 00:57:32.810
a lot of like what
you talked about

00:57:32.810 --> 00:57:34.995
has come from like your
personal experience

00:57:34.995 --> 00:57:36.980
and your personal story.

00:57:36.980 --> 00:57:39.210
You also talked about
the technical skills

00:57:39.210 --> 00:57:41.690
that you sought out to learn.

00:57:41.690 --> 00:57:46.680
So I was curious to know
how much of like what you're

00:57:46.680 --> 00:57:51.190
bringing to the table as
far as like your actual--

00:57:51.190 --> 00:57:53.370
the musical skills
and the writing

00:57:53.370 --> 00:57:57.454
skills came from a school
setting versus self-taught?

00:57:57.454 --> 00:58:00.120
BENJAMIN SCHEUER: Well, I have a
degree in English from Harvard.

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:05.310
And I spent a lot of time
reading and performing

00:58:05.310 --> 00:58:07.970
in theater and
studying structure,

00:58:07.970 --> 00:58:10.130
studying three-act structure.

00:58:10.130 --> 00:58:12.610
And so very, very quickly,
classical three-act structures.

00:58:12.610 --> 00:58:14.680
The first act is here
is your protagonist.

00:58:14.680 --> 00:58:15.880
Here is what they want.

00:58:15.880 --> 00:58:18.610
The second act is here's
why you can't have it

00:58:18.610 --> 00:58:20.970
and how they go off on their
journey to try to get it.

00:58:20.970 --> 00:58:25.320
And the third act is they get
it and they go home happy.

00:58:25.320 --> 00:58:26.820
That's a comedy.

00:58:26.820 --> 00:58:28.680
They don't get it and they die.

00:58:28.680 --> 00:58:31.000
That's a tragedy.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.247
Or they realize that they
actually really wanted

00:58:33.247 --> 00:58:35.580
something else all along, and
they get that other thing,

00:58:35.580 --> 00:58:37.413
and they kind of change
their point of view.

00:58:37.413 --> 00:58:38.570
And that's a drama.

00:58:38.570 --> 00:58:40.910
This has been going
on for 10,000 years,

00:58:40.910 --> 00:58:43.080
however long stories
have been told.

00:58:43.080 --> 00:58:45.120
And the thing about that
that I've taken away

00:58:45.120 --> 00:58:48.630
is I try to incorporate that
three-act structure that I've

00:58:48.630 --> 00:58:50.890
learned by studying
theater and literature

00:58:50.890 --> 00:58:54.060
into every single
song, into each song.

00:58:54.060 --> 00:58:56.000
And so, yeah, it's
very technical.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:59.950
"The Lion's" structure, the
piece of theater structure,

00:58:59.950 --> 00:59:02.360
is very much based on
Joseph Campbell, who's

00:59:02.360 --> 00:59:04.230
a 20th-century
American historian who

00:59:04.230 --> 00:59:05.460
codified the hero's journey.

00:59:05.460 --> 00:59:07.580
He was like, OK, what
do Buddha, and Jesus,

00:59:07.580 --> 00:59:09.620
and Moses, and Odysseus
all have in common?

00:59:09.620 --> 00:59:11.050
How are their stories similar?

00:59:11.050 --> 00:59:13.466
And he kind of worked out that
they all follow pretty much

00:59:13.466 --> 00:59:14.420
a similar trajectory.

00:59:14.420 --> 00:59:16.550
And so structurally,
yeah, I really

00:59:16.550 --> 00:59:18.220
try to be very technical.

00:59:18.220 --> 00:59:22.800
Because the closer I stay to
the technical structuralism,

00:59:22.800 --> 00:59:26.186
the farther I can go in
telling my version of that.

00:59:26.186 --> 00:59:29.210
And I've been very lucky to
study at the Johnny Mercer

00:59:29.210 --> 00:59:32.120
songwriting workshop.

00:59:32.120 --> 00:59:34.000
It's one week long.

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:36.760
It's hosted at
Northwestern University.

00:59:36.760 --> 00:59:39.020
And here's the way it works.

00:59:39.020 --> 00:59:41.690
You apply, if you're
18 to 30 years old.

00:59:41.690 --> 00:59:43.800
And you send in three tunes.

00:59:43.800 --> 00:59:45.990
And if you get in, they
buy you a plane ticket,

00:59:45.990 --> 00:59:47.120
and they give you
a bunch of money,

00:59:47.120 --> 00:59:49.036
and they bring you to
Northwestern for a week.

00:59:49.036 --> 00:59:51.800
And you just write with
three master teachers.

00:59:51.800 --> 00:59:54.020
Andrew Lippa is a
fabulous writer.

00:59:54.020 --> 00:59:56.790
He's got "Big Fish,"
and "Addam's Family,"

00:59:56.790 --> 00:59:59.100
and "I Am Harvey
Milk," the oratorio.

00:59:59.100 --> 01:00:00.670
Craig Carnelia is
another songwriter.

01:00:00.670 --> 01:00:02.430
Lari White is
another songwriter,

01:00:02.430 --> 01:00:04.763
the woman who told me if you
want to write a great song,

01:00:04.763 --> 01:00:07.300
if you want to
write a good song.

01:00:07.300 --> 01:00:08.607
And I just got paid to write.

01:00:08.607 --> 01:00:10.190
It was the first
time anybody had ever

01:00:10.190 --> 01:00:11.630
said you should do that.

01:00:11.630 --> 01:00:12.862
This is a job.

01:00:12.862 --> 01:00:14.070
And there are no assignments.

01:00:14.070 --> 01:00:16.140
But you go and you
write whatever you want.

01:00:16.140 --> 01:00:17.640
And then these three
master teachers

01:00:17.640 --> 01:00:18.974
will say-- you'll play a tune.

01:00:18.974 --> 01:00:21.390
And they'll say, oh, you know
the second verse is actually

01:00:21.390 --> 01:00:23.973
similar to this Dylan song that
maybe you haven't checked out.

01:00:23.973 --> 01:00:26.540
Or did you see Stephen
Sondheim's version of this song

01:00:26.540 --> 01:00:27.350
that you're doing?

01:00:27.350 --> 01:00:30.320
This is a I'm sad
you left song, or a

01:00:30.320 --> 01:00:33.720
I want you to love me song,
or a I want to change song.

01:00:33.720 --> 01:00:35.026
I mean it's all pretty similar.

01:00:35.026 --> 01:00:37.400
We're writing the same songs
again, and again, and again.

01:00:37.400 --> 01:00:38.930
It goes back to what we
were talking about earlier.

01:00:38.930 --> 01:00:40.610
It's not that our
stories are the same.

01:00:40.610 --> 01:00:42.820
But we feel the
same way about it.

01:00:42.820 --> 01:00:45.990
And it was extraordinary
to be able to work

01:00:45.990 --> 01:00:48.490
with these writers, these
professional writers,

01:00:48.490 --> 01:00:50.940
and to meet other young writers
who had similar ambitions.

01:00:50.940 --> 01:00:53.940
And so to be able to be part
of a community of songwriters

01:00:53.940 --> 01:00:56.180
is one of the most
valuable things.

01:00:56.180 --> 01:00:59.660
Because we'll talk about
how rhyme can be helpful,

01:00:59.660 --> 01:01:04.700
how enjambment can be helpful,
how setting up an expectation

01:01:04.700 --> 01:01:08.560
and then not fulfilling it
in a song can be helpful.

01:01:08.560 --> 01:01:10.440
And these are all
the technical tools.

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:13.320
And I very much believe
that learn the technique

01:01:13.320 --> 01:01:14.550
as much as you can.

01:01:14.550 --> 01:01:17.700
And then use it in support
of, rather than in place of,

01:01:17.700 --> 01:01:19.244
what you want to say.

01:01:19.244 --> 01:01:20.200
AUDIENCE: All right.

01:01:20.200 --> 01:01:22.382
ALAN SEALES: Thank you.

01:01:22.382 --> 01:01:23.840
AUDIENCE: I have
a simple question.

01:01:23.840 --> 01:01:27.290
What keeps you moving every
day, like what you keep doing?

01:01:27.290 --> 01:01:28.830
And what's the motivation?

01:01:28.830 --> 01:01:31.590
Where are you getting it from?

01:01:31.590 --> 01:01:34.280
BENJAMIN SCHEUER: I get a lot of
motivation from the audiences.

01:01:34.280 --> 01:01:36.030
And some days I wake
up and I'm like, man,

01:01:36.030 --> 01:01:37.488
I do not want to
go to the theater.

01:01:37.488 --> 01:01:38.130
I'm tired.

01:01:38.130 --> 01:01:39.450
And it's snowing outside.

01:01:39.450 --> 01:01:41.990
I'm like, I'm comfy in bed.

01:01:41.990 --> 01:01:42.990
And then I go do a show.

01:01:42.990 --> 01:01:45.573
And mean I met a young kid who
was 17 years old the other day,

01:01:45.573 --> 01:01:46.880
who's studying-- or 18 I guess.

01:01:46.880 --> 01:01:47.720
He's at NYU.

01:01:47.720 --> 01:01:51.880
And he's studying
songwriting and acting.

01:01:51.880 --> 01:01:55.490
And he said, man, you're
doing what I want to do.

01:01:55.490 --> 01:01:58.782
That's inspiring
that I don't know

01:01:58.782 --> 01:02:01.240
how I could write songs about
myself and it could be a job.

01:02:01.240 --> 01:02:02.156
But you're doing that.

01:02:02.156 --> 01:02:03.900
And that makes me want
to get out of bed.

01:02:03.900 --> 01:02:08.550
And I was like, OK, well,
that's pretty beautiful.

01:02:08.550 --> 01:02:10.820
I'm a pretty happy guy.

01:02:10.820 --> 01:02:16.830
I get to play guitar for a
job and wear red clothes.

01:02:16.830 --> 01:02:19.240
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:19.240 --> 01:02:20.439
It's pretty awesome.

01:02:20.439 --> 01:02:21.980
I love going to the
recording studio.

01:02:21.980 --> 01:02:24.396
I love working with Geoff
Kraly, who's my record producer.

01:02:24.396 --> 01:02:25.920
We've worked together for years.

01:02:25.920 --> 01:02:27.780
And we have the best time.

01:02:27.780 --> 01:02:31.360
We get to play with microphones,
and play with words,

01:02:31.360 --> 01:02:32.430
and play with melodies.

01:02:32.430 --> 01:02:34.346
And also I get to play
with some of the people

01:02:34.346 --> 01:02:35.980
I've always dreamed
about working with.

01:02:35.980 --> 01:02:37.340
That's one of the
coolest things.

01:02:37.340 --> 01:02:38.390
ALAN SEALES: Like Bruce Willis.

01:02:38.390 --> 01:02:39.430
BENJAMIN SCHEUER:
Like Bruce Willis.

01:02:39.430 --> 01:02:41.850
Well, in terms of the record
that I'm making for the show,

01:02:41.850 --> 01:02:44.362
I'm not just making a record
with guitar and vocals.

01:02:44.362 --> 01:02:45.570
That's how it is in the show.

01:02:45.570 --> 01:02:46.960
But on the record, I
was like, all right,

01:02:46.960 --> 01:02:48.810
well who are the people I've
always wanted to work with?

01:02:48.810 --> 01:02:50.950
And there's this one tune in the
show, its on electric guitar.

01:02:50.950 --> 01:02:52.640
It's kind of a Nine
Inch Nails thing.

01:02:52.640 --> 01:02:56.480
And I was like, why don't we
just hire Nine Inch Nails?

01:02:56.480 --> 01:02:57.620
They're just guys.

01:02:57.620 --> 01:02:58.520
You can call them.

01:02:58.520 --> 01:03:00.920
And so we called Josh
Freese, who plays drums

01:03:00.920 --> 01:03:03.500
in Nine Inch Nails, and with
Sting, and with Guns and Roses,

01:03:03.500 --> 01:03:05.510
and we said come play
on the record, man.

01:03:05.510 --> 01:03:08.610
And he sure, why not?

01:03:08.610 --> 01:03:11.059
And so that's incredibly
exciting to me.

01:03:11.059 --> 01:03:12.600
So something that
really motivates me

01:03:12.600 --> 01:03:15.190
is working with people
who are better than I am.

01:03:15.190 --> 01:03:18.114
If I can keep doing that,
I'll be a happy guy.

01:03:18.114 --> 01:03:20.280
ALAN SEALES: Well, thank
you so much for coming out.

01:03:20.280 --> 01:03:21.720
That was wonderful.

01:03:21.720 --> 01:03:22.680
[APPLAUSE]

01:03:22.680 --> 01:03:27.850
So we've got one more song
you're going to give us,

01:03:27.850 --> 01:03:32.230
to close out, that's not
so sad, not so cancery.

01:03:32.230 --> 01:03:35.280
So yeah, before you start,
I want to give you a plug.

01:03:35.280 --> 01:03:36.910
Everyone visit
thelionmusical.com,

01:03:36.910 --> 01:03:41.206
visit Benjamin online,
benjaminscheuer.com.

01:03:41.206 --> 01:03:42.150
The show is great.

01:03:42.150 --> 01:03:43.260
It's phenomenal.

01:03:43.260 --> 01:03:46.380
I can't go on-- I can go on
and on about how wonderful it

01:03:46.380 --> 01:03:47.960
and just how touching it is.

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:49.520
So I'm going to
get off the stage,

01:03:49.520 --> 01:03:51.220
give you your final moment.

01:03:51.220 --> 01:03:51.720
BENJAMIN SCHEUER:
Thank you very much.

01:03:51.720 --> 01:03:52.553
ALAN SEALES: Please.

